courses
Class Time

java.lang.Object
  courses.Time
All Implemented Interfaces:
java.lang.Comparable<Time>
public class Time
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.lang.Comparable<Time>

The time of day on a 24 hour clock. There is no representation of Days. Times are immutable.

Invariants:

  • 0 <= getHours() < 24
  • 0 <= getMinutes() < 60

Version:
May 30, 2011: compareTo implemented. Documentation added., May 29, 2011: class and constructor documentation, constructors implementation., May 19, 2011 (evening): getLaterTime removed; loosened restrictions on 2 arg constructor instead to accept negative values., May 19, 2011: class created, original signatures added.
Author:
Jonathan Caddey

Time

public Time(int the_hours,
            int the_minutes)
     throws java.lang.IllegalArgumentException
Constructs a Time given the_hours and the_minutes. Neither argument should be negative, but the time will be normalized if the_hours > 23 or the_minutes > 59.

Parameters:
the_hours - the hour of the day.
the_minutes - the minutes of the day.
Throws:
java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if the_hours < 0 or the_minutes < 0.

Time

public Time(int the_time)
     throws java.lang.IllegalArgumentException
Accepts the integer representation of the time, where the_time = hours * 100 + minutes. For example, to express 18:05, the_time should be 1805. No attempt will be made to normalize times where the hours is greater than 23 or the minutes is greater than 59.

Parameters:
the_time - the integer form of the desired time.
Throws:
java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if the_time < 0, the_time / 100 > 23, or the_time % 100 > 59.

Throws:

overlap

public static boolean overlap(Time the_start_1,
                              Time the_end_1,
                              Time the_start_2,
                              Time the_end_2,
                              int the_difference)
                       throws java.lang.IllegalArgumentException,
                              java.lang.NullPointerException
Returns whether two durations overlap. The durations are the times between the_start and the_end. The start time must be before the corresponding end time--i.e. no duration may start in the evening and end in the morning. The durations overlap if either duration ends within the_difference minutes of the other duration starting.

Preconditions:
  • the_start_1.compareTo(the_end_1) < 0
  • the_start_2.compareTo(the_end_2) < 0
Postconditions:
  • none

Parameters:
the_start_1 - the start of the first duration.
the_end_1 - the end of the first duration.
the_start_2 - the start of the second duration.
the_end_2 - the end of the second duration.
the_difference - the necessary time between the two durations.
Returns:
whether the two durations overlap.
Throws:
java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if either start is at a later time than their corresponding ends, or the_difference < 0.
java.lang.NullPointerException - if any argument is null.
